					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dreverettmann" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(323946); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=323946&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204982" alt="DrEverettMann" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=323946)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dreverettmann" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(323946); return false;" >DrEverettMann</a></span> <span class="odate time_1269331486 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">23 Mar 2010 08:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-731940">
									

<p>Oh, be honest, Bright. He's still an annoying little twit. But he grows on one, somehow. Rather like a fungus.</p>
<p>I arrived here about a year or so ago. April or May 2009. We were in the midst of the Hi-Jinx Era (as the historians will come to call it), and after writing up a couple of SCPs, I started in on the roleplay. By happenstance, I entered at about the same time as Waxx introduced Dmitri. It was a time of growth on the site, as people were pulling in a great number of directions. Some of these were good, some… less so. LBD was the primary GM for the roleplay, which caused it to veer strongly into the nonsensical. Kondraki was using the site more and more for his own self-aggrandizement, a continuous search for ways to further how cool he was (which was always much cooler than anyone else). More and more of the personalities were ending up in the articles, which caused the tone of the site to vary from the horrifying to the "wacky." It was fun, but it was not right for the site. On the other hand, this same looseness encouraged people to experiment more, I think, and encouraged new users to join. The sum of this would ultimately lead to the Great Purging, a consolidation of the site's narrative assets into a more cohesive whole. Articles, both new and old, were scrapped, while others were kept. A stronger vision of the site came out of the whole affair, and I believe the site is stronger for it. I was not involved in the mass edit, but I saw the results, and it was immediately evident how things had changed. I believe the site will continue to change and evolve, and, with work, improve.</p>
<p>On the other hand, some idiot made me Senior Staff. Clearly, we're all doomed. Terribly, terribly doomed.</p>

